english:
  title: Royal Reply to Sung Seok-rin's Request for Retirement
  language: eng
  text: |-
    You fear abundance and seek release from office—though your request springs from modesty, I appoint the worthy because I desire good governance. Moreover, the hopes of all people rest upon one of ripened wisdom, and your bearing shines as an exemplar in our court. How can I permit you to withdraw into leisure?

    You are a talent to guide the world, a virtue to administer the realm. Your learning penetrates the boundary between heaven and humanity; your vision comprehends the proper ways of ancient and modern times. Your principles align with statecraft—early you rose to the Three Excellencies, and your merits of aid and support befit the highest office. Since I inherited and assumed the throne, I have again relied upon you as elder statesman, that you might lead all the officials. For ten years you have unfolded your accumulated wisdom: you have stilled tremors and quelled tumult, and harmonized the bitter and sweet, the parched and damp. Laboring in all matters, constant in rectitude from beginning to end, I had hoped your noble counsel would flourish ever more, that all the myriad affairs of state might prosper.

    Yet seeing your recent petition, you wish to lay down this heavy burden. Your self-assessment may be wise, but what of my expectations? Alas! The Duke of Zhou rose as a worthy to aid King Wen's reign, and the Duke of Bi, though aged, remained to serve as teacher to the Zhou. How much more should one like you, an elder minister of undiminished reputation, feel no shame before the ancients? Therefore, come forth to tend to your duties—do not cling to illness as excuse for refusal.
  footnotes:
    - The title refers to Sung Seok-rin (成石璘), likely a historical official who requested retirement, and this is the ruler's rejection of that request.
    - The 'Three Excellencies' (三公) refers to the three highest ministerial positions in the traditional Chinese bureaucratic system.
    - References to the Duke of Zhou (尙父/呂尙) and Duke of Bi (畢公) invoke examples of sage ministers who served faithfully into old age, establishing the precedent being invoked here.
    - The imagery of 'bitter and sweet, parched and damp' suggests the balancing of opposing forces and the harmonious management of state affairs.
